# Architecture & Design Standards

> Read `~/.claude/memory/design-review.md` before implementing non-trivial features.

## Design Before Code
- Identify module/service boundaries and ownership first
- Define interfaces between boundaries before writing internals
- Test: "Can I swap, extend, or reuse this piece independently?"

## Boundary Design
- Narrow public APIs, hidden internals
- Depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations
- Co-locate what changes together; separate what changes independently

## Service Scope
- One service = one domain — flag features that introduce a second domain
- Prefer thin inter-service APIs (events, typed contracts) over shared DBs or direct calls
- If naming an endpoint feels forced, the feature belongs elsewhere

## Push Back When
- A task implies tight coupling across boundaries
- A feature requires modifying >2 unrelated modules
- A service is asked to own logic outside its domain — propose a new boundary
{{- end }}

# Tech Stack

- TypeScript across most repos
- Detect package manager: `yarn.lock` → yarn, `package-lock.json` → npm
- Never use `npx` — use `npm run`/`yarn` scripts; add a new script to `package.json` if none exists
- Python: use `uv` for everything (`uv run pytest`, `uv pip install`) — never bare `python`/`pip`
- JSON processing: use `jq` — never `python -m json.tool`

{{- if eq .role "work" }}

# Code Review

- Check out PR branches locally rather than repeated `gh api` / blob reads
- Human voice — positive, constructive, solution-oriented
- Suffix comments with `[ai authored; matt approved]`
